But, while there is no body or life hack to make you impervious to the touch of disease, we do know that sleep is key to helping our bodies stay healthy.
“Sleep is an essential part of protection from and response to any infection,” said Douglas B. Kirsch, a neurologist and former president of the American Academy of Sleep Medicine.
But still, he hears you: “Sleep is hard when anxiety levels are high, such as in the case of a pandemic.”There are some answers as to what you can do now.
Create and maintain a very consistent sleep practice and schedule that works for you.
The National Sleep Foundation recommends sticking to a sleep schedule, and here’s a simple way to do it: Set a regular bedtime.